# DONE — source-owned action adapters + Telegram controls

## Bottom line

Telegram has solid inline-keyboard plumbing, but the generic callback path is **not trustworthy enough for `Done`**.

It currently removes buttons and marks the callback complete when Inngest merely accepts the event, before the source mutation finishes:

- dispatch: `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:1621-1637`
- removes keyboard: `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:1641-1644`
- marks complete: `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:1656`
- actual worker: `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/telegram-callback.ts:47-288`

Worse, the automatic buttons in `packages/gateway/src/outbound/format.ts:8-34` emit actions such as `restart:worker`, `email:archive`, `loop:rerun`, and `memory:approve`. None has a matching in-tree generic handler. `memory:approve` also lacks the proposal ID required by `telegram-callback.ts:9,55-148`.

Those buttons look functional but aren’t. Don’t build source-owned `Done` on that path.

---

## 1. Telegram interaction capability

### Core keyboard sending

`InlineButton` already supports either callback data or a URL:

- `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:72-82`
- Telegram’s 64-byte callback limit is documented at line 74.
- `sendTelegramMessage()` converts buttons into `inline_keyboard`: `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:1968-2007`
- The keyboard is attached to the final message chunk: `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:2048-2051`

Therefore **Open source works today** as a URL button. It needs no callback handler.

Structured outbound envelopes can carry buttons:

- `packages/gateway/src/outbound/envelope.ts:3-15`
- routing merges explicit and inferred buttons: `packages/gateway/src/outbound/router.ts:145-166`
- registered Telegram channel sends them: `packages/gateway/src/daemon.ts:2164-2207`

Inngest producers can also send raw keyboards through `gateway/send.message`:

- event contract: `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/client.ts:1214-1228`
- queue envelope: `packages/system-bus/src/lib/channel-delivery-audit.ts:6-18`
- Redis delivery: `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/gateway-send-message.ts:20-69`
- daemon maps `callback_data` back to buttons: `packages/gateway/src/daemon.ts:5145-5154`

### Callback routing

The generic handler is `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:1366-1667`.

Routing order:

1. **Reply Grants** handled directly in the Telegram channel: `telegram.ts:1373-1500`.
2. `pitch:`, `mcq:`, `worktree:`, and `cmd:` are delegated to dedicated Grammy handlers: `telegram.ts:1506-1510`.
3. Dynamically registered prefixes, currently `restate:`, publish to Redis: `telegram.ts:1515-1595`.
4. Everything else emits `telegram/callback.received` to Inngest: `telegram.ts:1610-1637`.

The system-bus callback worker only understands:

- memory approve/reject with a proposal ID
- ADR pitch approve/reject
- o11y `s4h` snooze

Receipt: `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/telegram-callback.ts:6-10,55-288`.

### Specialized direct API paths

| UI | Builder | Callback handler |
|---|---|---|
| Command argument menus | `commands/telegram-handler.ts:199-225` | `commands/telegram-handler.ts:576-637` |
| Telegram command menu | `commands/telegram-handler.ts:736-778` | `bot.command()` at `:772` |
| Pinned status | `commands/telegram-handler.ts:385-437` | Direct Bot API edits; no callback |
| MCQ | `commands/mcq-adapter.ts:167-207` | `:214-279` |
| Worktree controls | `commands/worktree.ts:235-242` | `:244-344` |
| ADR pitch controls | `commands/telegram-handler.ts:666-733` | same handler |
| Reply Grants | buttons in `channels/slack.ts:200-205` | `channels/telegram.ts:1373-1500` |
| Restate approvals | `restate/src/channels/telegram.ts:43-111` | Redis route/listener at `:120-204` |

The Restate route is the best callback model today. It registers its prefix, performs the real downstream resolution, then publishes a terminal trace result:

- route registration: `packages/restate/src/channels/telegram.ts:120-142`
- source resolution: `:163-185`
- terminal callback result: `:185-199`
- gateway receives trace results: `packages/gateway/src/channels/telegram.ts:537-604`

Unlike the generic Inngest path, it does not claim completion merely because dispatch succeeded.

